<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06241181 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06241181 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Perez de Cuellar  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  IRAN; WORLD; COUNTRY; KIDNAPPING; ISRAEL; WOMEN  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Iran's representative at the United Nations conferred here Tuesday withSecretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar for 90 minutes. The envoy, KamalKharazzi, later told reporters that he had nothing new to say about thehostage situation in Lebanon but said he remained optimistic that it would beresolved.;   Perez de Cuellar was reported by Reuters to have accepted aninvitation to go to Tehran on Sept. 10 to discuss other issues and said hewould talk about the hostages if needed.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  IRANIAN ENVOY OPTIMISTIC ON HOSTAGES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     On Monday he said he hoped the hostage issue would be resolved before hewent to Iran. Reuters said that when asked about that on Tuesday, thesecretary general replied, &quot;Well, I wouldn't say settled, but I hope thatsomething positive will happen in between.&quot;;   In Washington, State Departmentofficials said Tuesday that they had no independent new information on thestatus of hostages.;   &quot;We support the efforts of the secretary general but wedo not have signs of impending releases,&quot; a State Department official said.;  When Kharazzi was asked about the fate of seven Israeli soldiers whosewhereabouts Israeli says must be disclosed before there is any hostage deal,the Iranian diplomat said: &quot;This information is in Lebanon if there is any.&quot;;  Israel has said it will not release the 375 Arabs it holds until it learnsthe whereabouts of the seven.;   &quot;Basically, what the Israelis claim abouttheir servicemen is something which is between Israel and the Lebanese,&quot;Kharazzi said. &quot;We can only help the secretary general to encourage theLebanese group to be more flexible and to release the hostages.&quot;;   Speakingof the Lebanese factions, he said: &quot;They have their own demands and they wanttheir own hostages released. We all have to be more attentive and responsiveto the grievances of the Lebanese people.;   In Beirut, Lebanon's Amal militiasaid it had the bodies of two missing Israeli soldiers and demanded thatIsrael free 28 women held prisoner before the Red Cross could examine thebodies.;   A senior Muslim official in Beirut, who declined to be identified,said, &quot;The bottom line is we are not willing to give the Israelis theinformation they request before Israel frees some of the Lebanese andPalestinan prisoners it holds.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Geneva, Switzerland  </CITY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910828  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  377  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, August 28, 199100241181,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>